ReplSetup.html.title: Repl Setup
ReplSetup.html.body:
Repl Setup for HTML/CSS
Create a Replit account in order to save and share HTML/CSS projects.

Go to the replit.com signup page
Fill out a username, email, and password, and click the "Sign up" button 
If necessary, prove your humanity to verify the account
On the next page, click the "Build from scratch" button 
In the next pop-up, select "HTML, CSS, JS" as the language
Click the "Create repl" button 

That's it! Now you have a Replit account and a Repl project. Be sure to remember the username, email, and password you used to sign up.
Repl Overview
Replit is a website that allows developers to write and run code right from a web browser!


Code Editor - This is where developers write code
Run Button - Developers click this button to execute the code
Run Area - This is where the developer sees the results of the code

In the new Repl, click the "run" button to see the code execute. Note that nothing should happen at this point; the webpage is still empty.
TIP - Boiler-plate Code
At the moment, there is a lot of "boiler-plate" code in the editor. Don't worry about that for now; you do not need to understand any of it yet!

Session5HtmlIntro/StudentDesc.html.body:
Hello HTML
Learn what HTML is all about, and how to use some of the basic HTML elements: headers, paragraphs, and images. Review the PowerPoint presentation, then get setup on Replit.com. After that, complete the About Me Code-Along activity, and work on the About Me Individual exercise. Beyond that, there are a couple of challenges to complete as well.
Basic HTML Elements PowerPoint Presentation


Activities

About Me Code-Along
About Me Individual

Session5HtmlIntro/AboutMeCodeAlong.html.title: About Me Code-Along
Session5HtmlIntro/AboutMeCodeAlong.html.body:
About Me: Code-Along
With this exercise, you will create a webpage that shows some information about yourself.
Making a Repl Account
Before beginning, make sure you have a Repl account. You can follow these instructions to set one up if you do not have one.
Getting Started
Start by creating a fork of an empty project to get started, and sharing a Multiplayer Link to the project.

Go to this empty Project
Click the "Fork" button in the upper right 
On the next page, click the "Share" button in the upper right 
In the window that appears, click the "Copy" button next to the link 

Once the Multiplayer Link has been copied, you can open this google form. Fill in your name, paste the link, and submit the form.
HTML Setup
Now everything should be ready to go. Start by creating a simple HTML document containing a header.

In the index.html file, add the  opening and closing tag
Inside of the  and , add the  opening and closing tag
Inside of the  and , add a  header tag that says "About Me"
Click the Run button to make sure your page is working!

At the end of the Setup, your code should look like this (try to match the spacing):

    
        About Me
    


Greeting and Basic Information
Next, add some additional information to the webpage.

Under the h1 header tag, add in a  paragraph tag welcoming the user to your page
Add another paragraph containing your name
Add another paragraph containing your grade level
Add another paragraph containing your favorite thing to do

At the end of this section, your code should look something like this:

    
        About Me

        Welcome to my page!
        My name is Arthur Read
        I am in 3rd grade
        I like to play with my dog
    


Favorite Animal
Add in a picture of your favorite animal.

Under the last p paragraph tag, add a smaller h3 header that says "Favorite Animal"
Add an image of your favorite animal
Find an image somewhere online, and copy the image URL
Add an  image tag under the h3 header
Set the src of the image to the URL, in quotes



Final HTML
The code should look something like this:

    
        About Me

        Welcome to my page!
        My name is Arthur Read
        I am in 3rd grade
        I like to play with my dog

        Favorite Animal

Session5HtmlIntro/AboutMeIndividual.html.title: About Me Individual
Session5HtmlIntro/AboutMeIndividual.html.body:
About Me: Individual
Continue the development of your "About Me" webpage.
Favorite Food
Add some more elements to your webpage that will describe your favorite foods. You will need to provide information about at least two foods you enjoy. Under the "Favorite Animal" img element, add another h3 header that says "Favorite Foods". Then, repeat the instructions below for two (or more) of your favorite foods.

Add a smaller h4 header with the name of your favorite food
Within the header, indicate the rank of this food (e.g., "1. Rice")


Add an image of your favorite food in an img image tag
Remember to set the src value to an image address


Add a brief description of your favorite food within a p paragraph

Other Favorites
In addition to listing some favorite foods, think of some of your other favorite things. Movies, songs, video games, athletes, or really anything else! Add more images and text to your webpage describing these other favorites.

Session6HtmlContinued/RestaurantCodeAlon.title: Restaurant Code-Along
Session6HtmlContinued/RestaurantCodeAlon.body:
Restaurant Website: Code-Along Activity
Congratulations, you just won $250,000 in a prestigious cooking competition! The only catch is that all of that money has to go toward starting a restaurant. You can serve any type of food you'd like, but you also have to make a website for your new endeavor. Follow the instructions below!
Setup
Make sure to log into your Repl account before proceeding!

Open and fork the empty Repl project to begin
In your new project, open up the index.html file
Add the html tags (opening and closing)
Add the body tags within the html tags

It should look something like this:

    
    


Adding the Basics
Add a header, image, and paragraph to the site. For this example, we will be making a Pizza restaurant - but feel free to choose a different food, and a different restaurant name.

Add an h1 header that says "Alfredo's Pizza Cafe" between the  and 
Under the h1, add an  of the pizza
Set the src attribute to "https://i.imgur.com/v4GLRqb.jpg"
Feel free to use a different image for a different restaurant


Under the img, add a p that says "WE'RE NOT FINE DINING; WE'RE JUST FINE FOOD!"
Note that this is the actual slogan of the actual Alfredo's Pizza Cafe


Open your webpage in a browser and make sure it appears as expected!

At the end of this section, your code should look like this:

    
        Alfredo's Pizza Cafe
        
        WE'RE NOT FINE DINING; WE'RE JUST FINE FOOD!
    


Adding a YouTube Video
One fun way to attract customers is to add a video to the site! This is possible using YouTube's built-in embedding feature.

Go to YouTube
Find a video that would make sense on your website (like this one for a pizza restaurant)
From the YouTube video, click on the "SHARE" button
In the pop-up, click on the "Embed" button
In the lower right corner, click "COPY" to copy the code
Go back into Replit, and paste the code into the index.html file, under the  element
Run the program, and verify that the video appears on the page!

It should look something like this:

    
        Alfredo's Pizza Cafe
        
        WE'RE NOT FINE DINING; WE'RE JUST FINE FOOD!

        

    


Adding a List of Locations
Next, it's important to list the locations for the restaurant.

Add an h2 header that says "Locations" under the 
Under the h2, add a new ul (unordered list)
Within the ul, add some locations within li elements
Note that the li elements are children of the ul element
There should be at least three locations


Open your webpage in a browser and make sure it appears as expected!

At the end of this section, your code should look something like this:

    
        Alfredo's Pizza Cafe
        
        WE'RE NOT FINE DINING; WE'RE JUST FINE FOOD!

        

        Locations
        
            Scranton, PA
            Albany, NY
            Utica, NY
        
    


Adding the Menu - A New Page
The website has information now, but we still need to add in a menu! The menu can be another page on the website - this way, it can stay separate from the main page. Start by adding a new file, filling out some basic HTML, and linking it from the index.html file.

In the Replit project, add a new file by clicking the "Add file" button
Enter the name menu.html for the new file
Open the new file, and add the basic elements: html and body
Within the body, add an h1 header that says "Menu"
Under that, add a p that says "No substitutions please"

The code in the menu.html file should look something like this:

    
        Menu
        No substitutions please
    


Linking to the New File
In order to actually see the new page, it will be necessary to link to it from the main page!

Open the index.html file for editing
Under the  element, create an a element
Set the src of the a element to be "menu.html"
Set the text of the a element to say "Menu

The a element should look something like this:
Menu

Run the program, and verify that it is possible to open the new Menu page!
Adding Specialty Pizzas
Now that the Menu page has been created, we need to add some food to it.

Open the menu.html file for editing
Make a new line under the  in the body
Add an h3 that says "Top Specialty Pizzas"
Under the , create a  element
This is an unordered list because these are ranked in order


Between the  and , add an  element
Between the  and , add the text "Hawaiian Pizza"
Continue this process and add two more  elements under the first one within the ol

The code for this part should look something like this:
Top Specialty Pizzas

    Hawaiian Pizza
    Meat Lovers Pizza
    Meat Haters Pizza


Run the program, and verify that the specialty pizzas appear on the menu!
Adding Toppings
Next, add a section that lists all the toppings a customer can add.

Under the  in the body, make a new line
Add an h3 that says "Toppings"
Under the , create a  element
Between the  and , add an  element
Between the  and , add the text "Pepperoni"
Continue this process and add two more  elements under the first one within the ul

The code for this part should look something like this:
Toppings

    Pepperoni
    Mushroom
    Extra Cheese


Run the program, and verify that the toppings list appears on the menu!
Linking Back
Currently, after a customer visits the menu, they cannot get back to the main page. We can fix this with another a element on the Menu page.

Under the final , make a new line
Add an a element
Set its href attribute to index.html
Set its text content to Back



It should look something like this:
Back

Run the program, and verify that it is possible to go to the Menu page and go back!
Final HTML
By the end, the two files should look something like this:
index.html

    
        Alfredo's Pizza Cafe
        
        WE'RE NOT FINE DINING; WE'RE JUST FINE FOOD!

        

        Locations
        
            Scranton, PA
            Albany, NY
            Utica, NY
        
        Menu
    


menu.html

    
        Menu
        No substitutions please

        Top Specialty Pizzas
        
            Hawaiian Pizza
            Meat Lovers Pizza
            Meat Haters Pizza
        

        Toppings
        
            Pepperoni
            Mushroom
            Extra Cheese
        

        Back

Session6HtmlContinued/RestaurantIndividu.title: Restaurant Individual
Session6HtmlContinued/RestaurantIndividu.body:
Restaurant Website: Individual Exercises
The website for Alfredo's Pizza Cafe (or your own restaurant) is pretty solid, but there are some changes you can make to take it to the next level. Follow the instructions below to add some new features to your website!
Part 1 - Expanding the Existing Options
Great news! Your restaurant is expanding its offerings. There is a new location, a new specialty item, and a new topping. The website should reflect those changes.
Adding a New Location
First, add another location to the list of locations.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the  element that lists restaurant locations
Under the existing  elements, above the , make a new line
Add a new  element with a new location, like "Cleveland, OH"
Run the site and make sure the new location appears in the list!

It should look something like this:

    Scranton, PA
    Albany, NY
    Utica, NY
    Cleveland, OH


Adding a New Specialty Item
Next, add another specialty item to the list of specialty items.

Open the menu.html file for editing
Find the  element that lists specialty items
Under the existing  elements, above the , make a new line
Add a new  element with a new specialty item, like "Margherita Pizza"
Run the site, open the menu, and make sure the new item appears in the list!

Adding a New Topping
Finally, add another topping to the list of toppings.

Open the menu.html file for editing
Find the  element that lists toppings
Under the existing  elements, above the , make a new line
Add a new  element with a new topping, like "Olives"
Run the site, open the menu, and make sure the new item appears in the list!

Part 2 - Size Options
For several types of food (including pizza), customers may want to decide what size portion they would like. For this restaurant, let's say we want two size options: Small and Large. List these options on the Menu page!

Open the menu.html file for editing
Under the  for the toppings, but above the  link, make a new line
Add an  header that says "Size Options"
Under that, create a  list
Between the  and , add an  element with text "Small"
Under that, above the , add another  saying "Large"
Run the site, open the menu, and make sure the size options appear!

Part 3 - Crust Options
Many pizza restaurants have different options for crusts. This could also be applied for other types of restaurants - for example, tacos could have hard or soft shells, sushi could have white or brown rice, etc. List these options on the Menu page!

Open the menu.html file for editing
Under the  for the size options, but above the  link, make a new line
Add an  header that says "Crust Options"
Under that, create a  list
Between the  and , add an  element with text "Thin"
Under that, above the , add another  saying "Deep Dish"
Run the site, open the menu, and make sure the crust options appear!

(CHALLENGE) Part 4 - An "About Us" Page
Sometimes customers want to learn more about a restaurant. This can be accomplished with an "About Us" Page! Create the new page, and link it from the home page.
The New Page
Start by creating the new page.

Add a new file to the Replit project
Name the file about.html
Open the file for editing
Add some basic HTML to the file
The  and  tags
A  in the body that says "About Us"
A  under the h1 with a short blurb about the restaurant


Under the , add an 
Set the href for the a to be "index.html"
Make the text for the a say "Back"

Linking to the New Page
Now the page exists, but it is not accessible yet! Add a link to the homepage.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the Menu above the 
Right under that, add a new 
Set the href for the a to be "about.html"
Make the text for the a say "About Us"

Run the code, and verify that it is possible to open the "About Us" page!

Session7CssIntro/CoolorsWarmUp.html.title: Coolors Warm-up
Session7CssIntro/CoolorsWarmUp.html.body:
Warm-up: Color Scheme Creation
Follow these instructions to create a custom color scheme.


Go to coolors.co
Close out of the initial pop-up(s)
Click the "Start the generator!" button
Close out of the pop-up
Press the space bar to randomize the color scheme
Press the "lock" button on a color you like to hold it
Continue to press space and lock colors you like
Remove colors by click the "x" button
When you have a scheme you like, click the "Export" button
In the pop-up, click the "Copy URL" button
Paste the URL to share it!

Session7CssIntro/BananasIndividual.html.title: Bananas Individual
Session7CssIntro/BananasIndividual.html.body:
Go Bananas: Individual Exercises
The banana product page looks much more exciting than a simple HTML page, but it could look even better. Follow the instructions below to update the page with even more styles.
Part 1 - Updating Existing Rulesets
Start by updating some of the existing properties.
Changing the Text Color
The darkblue color is a little too strong. Change it to a lighter blue color that still maintains a contrast with the yellow background.

In the style.css file, find the body ruleset
In the body ruleset, find the declaration for the color property
Update the value of the color property from darkblue to steelblue

Run the code, and verify that the text changes color!
Changing the Main Header Font
Update the main header font so it looks even more fun.

In the style.css file, find the h1 ruleset
In the h1 ruleset, find the declaration for the font-family property
Update the value of the font-family property from cursive to jokerman

Run the code, and verify that the font changes!
Making the Images Larger
The images on the page are a little small. Make them bigger!

In the style.css file, find the img ruleset
In the img ruleset, find the declaration for the height property
Update the value of the height property from 150px to 200px

Run the code, and verify that the images get bigger!
Part 2 - Creating Additional Rulesets
Next, add some new rulesets to change other parts of the HTML page.
Updating the Color of the Section Headers
The section headers should match the background more effectively. Update the CSS so that the headers are a dark gold color.

In the style.css file, create a new ruleset for h2
Place the new ruleset beneath the existing rulesets (under })
Use the h2 selector and curly brackets ({}) to open the new block


Within the curly brackets, create a new declaration that sets the text color
Property: color
Value: darkgoldenrod



It should look something like this:
h2 {
    color: darkgoldenrod;
}

Updating the Font of the Reviewer Names
The reviewer names should have a different font to differentiate them from the rest of the text on the page.

In the style.css file, create a new ruleset for h3 (reviewer names are in these headers)
Within the ruleset, create a new declaration that sets the font
Property: font-family
Value: cursive



(CHALLENGE) Part 3 - New Product
Update the HTML on the page so that it is about a different product! Change the text, images, and anything else. The same styles should apply to any new HTML!
(CHALLENGE) Part 4 - Adding Style to Other Projects
Find some of the previous HTML projects you have created. Try to figure out how to add some CSS to make them more fun.

Start by creating a new style.css file in the Replit project
Then, link the file from the HTML
It should look something like 


Finally, add some CSS styles! Feel free to copy and paste from the Banana website.

Session8CssSelectors/RainbowCodeAlong.ht.title: Rainbow Code-Along
Session8CssSelectors/RainbowCodeAlong.ht.body:
Rainbow Coalition: Code-Along Activity
Add some styling to a website with information about the First Rainbow Coalition.
Current Webpage
So far, there is a website about the Rainbow Coalition with a couple of pages. The information is good, but the site could definitely use some styling.

Go to the existing Replit project
Fork the project by clicking the fork button
Make sure to log into your account!


Take a look at the code so far

There is an index.html file, a gallery.html, and a style.css file. The CSS file is already properly linked to both the home page and the gallery page.
Basic Changes
Start by making some basic changes that will apply to the entire website.
Body Changes
Set the whole page to dark mode (white text on black background) using the body selector.

Open the style.css file for editing
At the top of the file, create a new ruleset for the body
body { }


Within the body ruleset, set the background to black
background: black;


Under that, set the color to white
color: white;


Run the code, and verify that the page is now in dark mode!

The code should look something like this:
body {
    background: black;
    color: white;
}

Image Changes
Resize all of the images using the img selector.

Outside of the body ruleset (under }), make a new line
Add a ruleset for img
In the img ruleset, set height to 200px
Run the code, go to the gallery, and verify that each image is smaller

The code should look something like this:
img {
    height: 200px;
}

Link Changes
Currently, the hyperlinks on the page are difficult to see. Change the color of all hyperlinks using the a selector.

Outside of that ruleset (under }), make a new line
Add a ruleset for a
In the a ruleset, set color to lightblue
Run the code, and verify that each link is light blue.

The code should look something like this:
a {
    color: lightblue;
}

Changing the Main Header Color
Next, it's time to change the main header color. This should not apply to all headers, so it will be necessary to use a class! Update the HTML to add a class attribute to the h1, and then update the CSS to style it.
Updating the HTML
First, make the changes in the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the top  element
Make a space after the h1 (before >) and add the class attribute
class
=
""


Between the quotes, put red

The header should look like this:
The Rainbow Coalition

Nothing will happen yet, though!
Updating the CSS
Now that the HTML has been modified, it will be possible to select the specific header using the class attribute value.

Open the style.css file for editing
Under the existing rulesets, make a new line
Create a new ruleset selecting all elements with a class of red
.red { }


In the .red ruleset, set the color to salmon
color: salmon;


Run the code, and verify that only the main header changes to light red!

The new ruleset should look something like this:
.red {
    color: salmon;
}

Rainbow Paragraphs
The goal is to have each paragraph on the page be a different color of the rainbow. These updates will be very similar to updating the header - just with different elements and colors!
The First Paragraph
For the first paragraph, we can reuse the existing .red style.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the first  element on the page
Add a class attribute to the  with a value of red
Run the code, and verify that the top paragraph turns light red!

The paragraph should look something like this:
The Original Rainbow Coalition, formed in Chicago in the late 1960s, was the alliance between the Chicago Black Panther Party, Puerto Rican Young Lords, and Poor White Young Patriots Organization.

Note that no CSS changes are required - it applies the same .red style to any HTML element with class="red"!
The Second Paragraph
For the second paragraph, it will be necessary to create some new CSS. The goal is to make this paragraph orange.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the second  element
Add a class attribute to the  with a value of orange
Open the style.css file for editing
At the bottom, create a new ruleset to select by class="orange"
In the .orange ruleset, set the color to orange
Run the code, and verify that the second paragraph turns orange!

The paragraph should look like this:
It was one of the moments in the history of this country where the working class came together across racial lines to build power, support each other, and fight for their shared interests.

The ruleset should look like this:
.orange {
    color: orange;
}

The Third and Fourth Paragraphs
The third and fourth paragraphs should be updated in a very similar way. The third paragraph should be yellow, and the fourth paragraph should be green (using lightgreen as the actual color). Follow the same steps:

Find the proper  element in the index.html file
Set the class attribute to the color name
Make a new ruleset for the color in the style.css file
Set the color property to the proper color

The HTML code should look like this:
The Original Rainbow Coalition represented a real threat to the established powers both locally in Chicago and nationally.
The Chicago police conspired with the FBI to assassinate Fred Hampton, one of the key figures from the Black Panther Party, in his bed and to seriously undermine the Rainbow Coalition effort.

The CSS should look like this:
.yellow {
    color: yellow;
}

.green {
    color: lightgreen;
}

By this point, the paragraphs should form a nice rainbow of color!
Reusing the Yellow Class
One of the good things about creating class styles is that they can be reused. Reuse the .yellow ruleset to style the header on the gallery page.

Open the gallery.html file for editing
Find the  element on the page
Add a class attribute to the  with a value of yellow
Run the code, and verify that the header turns yellow!

The header should look something like this:
Gallery

Italic Source
The next thing to do is italicize the source  element. Since there is only one of these, we can use an id attribute/selector.
Updating the HTML
First, make the changes in the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the  element at the bottom with the source information
Make a space after the p (before >) and add the id attribute
id
=
""


Between the quotes, put footnote

The header should look like this:
Source: Kairos Center

Nothing will happen yet, though!
Updating the CSS
Now that the HTML has been modified, it will be possible to select the specific paragraph using the id attribute value.

Open the style.css file for editing
Under the existing rulesets, make a new line
Create a new ruleset selecting all elements with a id of footnote
#footnote { }


In the #footnote ruleset, set the font-style to italic
font-style: italic;


Run the code, and verify that only the source paragraph becomes italic!

The new ruleset should look something like this:
#footnote {
    font-style: italic;
}

Highlighted Image
Next, it's time to add a border to one of the images (but only the main one). This will be similar to the process of selecting the one  by its id, but it will be with an img instead, and the style property will be different.
Updating the HTML
First, make the changes in the HTML.

Open the gallery.html file for editing
Find the third  element
Make a space after the img (before src="") and add the id attribute
id
=
""


Between the quotes, put main-img

The image should look like this:


Nothing will happen yet, though!
Updating the CSS
Now that the HTML has been modified, it will be possible to select the specific image using the id attribute value.

Open the style.css file for editing
Under the existing rulesets, make a new line
Create a new ruleset selecting all elements with a id of main-img
#main-img { }


In the #main-img ruleset, set the border to 2px solid yellow
border: 2px solid yellow;


Run the code, and verify that only the main image has a yellow border!

The new ruleset should look something like this:
#main-img {
    border: 2px solid yellow;
}

Final Code
The website looks much more interesting now! The files at the end should look something like this:
index.html

  
    
  
  
    The Rainbow Coalition

    The Original Rainbow Coalition, formed in Chicago in the late 1960s, was the alliance between the Chicago Black Panther Party, Puerto Rican Young Lords, and Poor White Young Patriots Organization.
    It was one of the moments in the history of this country where the working class came together across racial lines to build power, support each other, and fight for their shared interests.
    The Original Rainbow Coalition represented a real threat to the established powers both locally in Chicago and nationally.
    The Chicago police conspired with the FBI to assassinate Fred Hampton, one of the key figures from the Black Panther Party, in his bed and to seriously undermine the Rainbow Coalition effort.

    Gallery

    Source: Kairos Center
  


gallery.html

  
    
  
  
    Gallery
    
      Back
    

    
    
    
    
  


style.css
body {
  background: black;
  color: white;
}

img {
  height: 200px;
}

a {
  color: lightblue;
}

.red {
  color: salmon;
}

.orange {
  color: orange;
}

.yellow {
  color: yellow;
}

Session8CssSelectors/RainbowIndividual.h.title: Rainbow Individual
Session8CssSelectors/RainbowIndividual.h.body:
Rainbow Coalition: Individual Exercises
The Rainbow Coalition page looks much more exciting than a simple HTML page, but it could look even better. Follow the instructions below to update the page with even more styles.
Part 1 - Updating The Green
Start by updating the green color so that it pops a little more.

Open the style.css file for editing
Find the .green ruleset
Change the lightgreen to lime
Run the program, and verify that the green paragraph stands out!

Part 2 - A New Paragraph
Add another paragraph to the home page, and make it cyan. For the text of the paragraph, use this:
Despite this loss, the spirit of the Rainbow Coalition lives on in various civil rights movements and groups even today.
HTML
Start by adding the  in the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the last informational paragraph
Under that, above the , add a new  element
For the text content, use the sentence above
Add a class attribute to the  element
Set the value of the class to cyan

Run the code, and verify that the new paragraph appears!
CSS
Next, add the ruleset in the CSS to to change the color.

Open the style.css file for editing
Make a new line at the bottom of the file (outside of any ruleset)
Create a new ruleset selecting elements with class cyan
Remember, this is .cyan { }


In the ruleset (between { and }), set the color to cyan
Remember, this is color: cyan;



Run the code, and verify that the new paragraph turns a bright blue color!
Part 3 - Bigger Back Link
Next, embiggen the "Back" link on the gallery page so it is a little easier to see.
HTML
Start by adding an id attribute to the p that contains the "Back" link.

Open the gallery.html page for editing
Find the  element that surrounds the  linking back
Add an id attribute to the  element
Set the value of the id to back-link

This should not change the appearance yet... we need CSS for that.
CSS
Add some CSS to style the "Back" link based on its id attribute value.

Open the style.css file for editing
Make a new line at the bottom of the file (outside of any ruleset)
Create a new ruleset selecting the element with id back-link
Remember, this is #back-link { }


In the ruleset (between { and }), set the font-size to 24px
Remember, this is font-size: 24px;



Run the code, and verify that the "Back" link on the gallery page is larger!
(CHALLENGE) Part 4 - More Research
Try to find some more information about Fred Hampton and the Rainbow Coalition. Search google and try to find some more text and images to fill out the webpage. Add the information/images to the files in the proper places, and try to style them appropriately.

Session9Grid/PixelsCodeAlong.html.title: Pixels Code-Along
Session9Grid/PixelsCodeAlong.html.body:
Pixels: Code-Along Activity
Create a CSS grid containing some pixel art.

Pixel Art Examples
Original Mario

All art for video games was once hand-coded, pixel-by-pixel!
Panda
(animated: https://i.imgur.com/ghillV4.gif)

Now, some developers copy this style for their own art
Landscape

Pixel art can be used for almost anything!
Starting Point
Get started by forking the existing Repl.

Go to the existing Replit project
Fork the project by clicking the fork button
Make sure to log into your account!


Take a look at the code so far

There should be nothing on the page - not yet anyway.
Main Div
First, add the main  element. This will contain all the cells for the pixels.
HTML
Start by creating the div in the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Make a new line between the  and 
There, add a new  element
Give the div an id of main

The HTML should look something like this:




It won't look like anything yet - it needs some CSS!
CSS
Next, add some CSS to the div.

Open the style.css file for editing
Create a new ruleset for the main div
Remember, this is #main { }


Within the ruleset, set the width to 400px
Under that, still within the ruleset, add a border
It should be 2px thick
It should be solid
It should be black



The CSS should look something like this:
#main {
    width: 400px;
    border: 2px solid black;
}

Run the code, and verify that something appears! It should be the right width, but it still has no content...
First Cell
It's time to add a cell to the container!
HTML
Start by creating another div in the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Make a new line between the  and 
There, add a new  element
Give the div a class of cell

The HTML should look something like this:

    


It won't look like anything yet - it needs some CSS!
CSS
Next, add some CSS to the cell div.

Open the style.css file for editing
Create a new ruleset for elements with class cell
Remember, this is .cell { }


Within the ruleset, set the height to 100px

The CSS should look something like this:
.cell {
    height: 100px;
}

Run the code, and verify that the whole container changes height! That's because it contains a cell.
First Row
Now there is one cell, but the grid needs four cells for each row. Start by putting together the first row.
HTML
First, add some more div elements to the HTML.

Open the index.html file for editing
Make a new line under the existing cell div
This should still be within 


There, add a new  element
Add two more cell div elements, all children of the main div

The HTML should look something like this:

    
    
    
    


The website should not look different yet.
CSS
Now that the cells exist, they need to take up the proper amount of space.

Open the style.css file for editing
Find the #main ruleset
Within the ruleset, set the display to grid
Under that, set the grid-template-columns property
There should be four equal columns
This can be accomplished with 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr



The CSS should look something like this:
#main {
    width: 400px;
    border: 2px solid black;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;
}

The website should not look different yet - but now the cells are in place, and they can be styled!
Yellow
Now it's time to actually style these cells! Start by styling the two yellow cells in PAC-MAN's head.
HTML
Start by updating the HTML - telling it which cells should be yellow.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the second cell div
Add yellow to its class attribute list
Make a space after cell, within the "", and put yellow


Add a class of yellow to the fourth cell div as well

The HTML should look something like this:

    
    
    
    


The cells still won't be yellow yet - they need some CSS.
CSS
Select the proper cells with CSS, and make them yellow!

Create a new ruleset for elements with class yellow
Remember, this is .yellow { }


Within the ruleset, set the background to gold

The CSS should look something like this:
.yellow {
    background: gold;
}

Run the code, and verify that two yellow pixels appear in the top row!
The Eye
To complete the top row, we need one black pixel in between the two yellow ones.
HTML
Start by updating the HTML - telling it which cell should be black.

Open the index.html file for editing
Find the third cell div
Add black to its class attribute list
Make a space after cell, within the "", and put black



The HTML should look something like this:

    
    
    
    


The cells still won't be black yet - they need some CSS.
CSS
Select the proper cells with CSS, and make them black!

Create a new ruleset for elements with class black
Remember, this is .black { }


Within the ruleset, set the background to black

The CSS should look something like this:
.black {
    background: black;
}

Run the code, and verify that the whole top row is what it should be! It should have a white square, a yellow square, a black square, and another yellow square.
The Rest
Now, all the CSS is done. The only thing that's left is to add more cell div elements within the main div. The cells will continue on to the next row, so just add  elements with the proper classes. Each div should have a class of cell. Some should have a class of yellow, and some should have a class of black - each cell in the PAC-MAN corresponds to one of the cell div elements.

For example, the next cell to add is the fifth one - it should be yellow.

    
    
    
    

    


This should add a new row. Continue adding each cell until the entire picture is complete!
Final Code
By the end of the activity, the code should look something like this:
index.html

    
        
    
    
        
            
            
            
            

            
            
            
            

            
            
            
            

            
            
            
            
        
    


style.css
#main {
    width: 400px;
    border: 2px solid black;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr 1fr;
}

.cell {
    height: 100px;
}

.yellow {
    background: gold;
}

.black {
    background: black;
}

Session9Grid/PixelsIndividual.html.title: Pixels Individual
Session9Grid/PixelsIndividual.html.body:
Pixels: Individual Exercise
Update the grid with some different artwork.
Part 1 - Red PAC-MAN
Instead of yellow, make PAC-MAN red!

Change the name of the "yellow" class to "red"
Change the class attribute value for each yellow div in the HTML
Change the .yellow ruleset so that it points to elements with a class of "red"


Change the background color from gold to red for those cells

Part 2 - Smaller PAC-MAN
Make updates so that each pixel in the grid is 50x50 instead of 100x100.

Set the width of the main div to 200px
This is in the #main ruleset


Set the height of each cell to 50px instead of 100px
This is in the .cell ruleset



Part 3 - Make Your Own Sprite
Instead of PAC-MAN, create a totally different 4x4 pixel art character! Feel free to copy one of the designs from here.
For a good starting point, try recreating one of the Tetris blocks:


In the CSS file, create a new class ruleset for each color used in the sprite
For example, in the long Tetris block, there could be a .green selector


In each color ruleset, set the background color to the appropriate color
Property: background
Value: color for the cell


In the HTML file, add an appropriate color class to each div
For example, in the long Tetris block, the third cell in each row could have the green class



(CHALLENGE) Make a 5x5 Sprite
It's hard to represent a character in only 32 cells. Instead of using a 4x4 grid, update the code so that it's 5x5. Then, create a new 5x5 sprite using the extra space!


In the CSS file, update the main div to have a width of 250px
In same ruleset, update the grid-template-columns to specify 5 columns instead of 4
In the HTML file, add an additional "cell" div for each new cell
Each new "cell" div should have a class attribute with value "cell"
There should be 9 new  elements total 


Update all the classes for the cells to reflect the new sprite!

Session10FinalProject/StudentDesc.html.title: Session 10: Final Project
Session10FinalProject/StudentDesc.html.body:
Final Project - Capstone
It's time to show off what you've learned! For the final project, create a website all about yourself.
Technical Requirements
You have a lot of freedom with this project, but you should make sure to meet some basic requirements.

At least two HTML pages
There should be links between pages as well


At least three styles
e.g., background color, color, font


At least one list
At least one image

Advanced Requirements
To go above and beyond with the project, there are some additional requirements.

Use a  element in HTML
Use a grid to separate parts of a page
Use an id to style with CSS
Use a class to style with CSS
Embed a YouTube video on one page

Content Requirements
The content can be anything you would like to share about yourself. Try to keep it professional and show us the best version of you!
